<AbstractNarration>Research in theoretical elementary particle physics will focus on the&lt;br/&gt;properties of nuclear matter in extreme environments, such as high&lt;br/&gt;temperatures or high density. Phase transitions are expected in these&lt;br/&gt;situations between conventional matter approximating the interior of a&lt;br/&gt;large nucleus and new, highly exotic large-scale states of matter in which&lt;br/&gt;there may be superfluidity, superconductivity and plasmas of unconfined&lt;br/&gt;quarks and gluons, the constituents of nuclear matter. Computer&lt;br/&gt;simulations as well as precise, analytic methods based on the theory of&lt;br/&gt;symmetries, will be employed to search for these new phenomena. These&lt;br/&gt;studies are important because they may tell us about conditions in the&lt;br/&gt;early universe.</AbstractNarration>
